hints_latex:
We expect the integral to diverge, since $\int_1^\infty \frac1{x}\,dx$
diverges. Hence, you want to show that

\begin{align*}
\frac1{1+2x} \geq C \frac1{x}
\end{align*}

and then use the integral comparison test.

sols_latex:
Evaluating directly, we see that

\begin{align*}
\int_{1}^{\infty}\frac{dx}{1 + 2x} &= \lim_{b \to\infty} \int_{1}^{b}\frac{dx}{1 + 2x} \\
&= \lim_{b \to\infty} \left.\frac{\ln|1+2x|}{2}\right|_{1}^{b} \\
&= \lim_{b \to\infty} \frac{\ln|1+2b|}{2} - \frac{\ln(3)}{2} 
\end{align*}

and this last limit diverges.

Following hints 3 and 4, we want to show that

\begin{align*}
\frac1{1+2x}\geq C \frac1{x}.
\end{align*}

A fraction is larger when the denominator is smaller, hence we can use

\begin{align*}
1+2x \leq x+2x = 3x
\end{align*}

to write

\begin{align*}
\frac1{1+2x} \geq \frac1{3x}.
\end{align*}

Thus, by the integral comparison test,

\begin{align*}
\int_1^\infty \frac1{1+2x}\,dx \geq \frac13 \int_1^\infty \frac1{x}\,dx
\end{align*}

However, the latter integral diverges by the integral \emph{p}-test
(\emph{p} = 1), and thus the former integral also diverges.
